body: This should've worked. Can you make sure the ```OMP_NUM_THREADS``` env variable is getting set correctly?
Are you still seeing this issue? Did you verify the value of the env variable?

I figured out that the env variable needs to be set _before_ the `onnxruntime` import. For instance,

```
import os
os.environ["OMP_NUM_THREADS"] = "1"
import onnxruntime

... rest of the code
```

Is it possible to have this behavior built into the `onnxruntime` package, so that intra/inter thread session options would have the expected effect? I think that would be less confusing for end users

Glad your issue is resolved. We could possibly use omp_set_num_threads/omp_get_num_threads to set the number of openmp threads. However, this is not the only variable that impacts performance. The wait policy also matters significantly which cannot be changed programatically. Besides we're trying to get rid of openmp usage in ORT. Please re-open if you've any further questions.

issue.title: Abnormal performance of SetIntraOpNumThreads(1)

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
After adding "sessionops.SetIntraOpNumThreads(1);" the CPU usage of my onnxruntime application went up to 100%. On the contrary, the default threads number only occupies 15% CPU.
What's going on? BTW 100% usage is slower than 15%. Is onnx wasting my CPU time? 

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Win10 64
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.1.0
- Python version: null
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): VS2019
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): null
- CUDA/cuDNN version: null
- GPU model and memory: null

**Expected behavior**
Single-thread or Multi-thread? I'm confused.

body:
@pranavsharma I'm working on another project with ORT - this time I `pip installed` version 1.5.1. Monitoring via `htop`, it seems that the default thread behavior has changed since `v1.2.0` from all threads to half of available threads (in my case 6 of 12). 

By setting the `OMP_NUM_THREADS` environment variable to 1 before `import onnxruntime` like I mentioned before, I am able to throttle the engine back to just one core - which is good. However, if I set the environment variable to my max threads (12) and adjust the session options `intra/inter_op_num_threads` to match, I still only get 6 of 12 threads activated. Is there a new built-in limit that is preventing me from using 100% of my cores?

@addisonklinke could you please provide more information? We can't reproduce the problem you described.  BTW, could you leave intra/inter_op_num_threads options to their default value? The official build was built with openmp, setting intra_op_num_threads doesn't help.

Which onnxruntime package did you installed, the GPU one or CPU one?

@snnn I've installed the CPU Python binding from PyPI and setup my session with the following code

```python
import os
os.environ['OMP_NUM_THREADS'] = '12'
import onnxruntime

opts = onnxruntime.SessionOptions()
opts.inter_op_num_threads = 12
opts.intra_op_num_threads = 12
ort_session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession('model.onnx', sess_options=opts)
```

If I skip creating the `opts` object and setting `iter/intra_op_num_threads`, I am still stuck at the default half thread count of 6 even though I specified 12 with `OMP_NUM_THREADS`. Could you try reproducing with a model from the zoo? That way I could test the same one on my machine if the issue does not occur for you

Hi @addisonklinke 
I wonder if you would like try the following package instead:

https://pypi.org/project/onnxruntime-noopenmp/

It was built without openmp, so things would be simpler.  Please manually uninstall your existing onnxruntime package before installing the new one.

Then all you need to do is just creating an SessionOptions object and set intra_op_num_threads to the number you want. like:

```
opts = onnxruntime.SessionOptions()
opts.intra_op_num_threads = 12
ort_session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession('model.onnx', sess_options=opts)
```
It is simpler, so it will give us less surprise.

> I figured out that the env variable needs to be set _before_ the `onnxruntime` import. For instance,
> 
> ```
> import os
> os.environ["OMP_NUM_THREADS"] = "1"
> import onnxruntime
> 
> ... rest of the code
> ```
> 
> Is it possible to have this behavior built into the `onnxruntime` package, so that intra/inter thread session options would have the expected effect? I think that would be less confusing for end users

Thanks a lot. it works perfectly. this correlated problem has haunted me for a whole week. damn, thanks a lot.

> I am still stuck at the default half thread count of 6 even though I specified 12 with OMP_NUM_THREADS.

@addisonklinke are you by a chance on CPUs with hyper threading?
```
In [1]: import psutil

In [2]: psutil.cpu_count()
Out[2]: 64

In [3]: psutil.cpu_count(logical=False)
Out[3]: 32
```
I'm asking because I think that `htop` shows the former (i.e. logical ones) on its CPU meters, while OMP uses the latter (i.e. physical ones).
